GluN2A GOF mutant rescue in DKO: NMDA-EPSC decay

Document format
Great tutorial for [R Markdown] (https://rmarkdown.rstudio.com/articles_intro.html)
R Markdown reports rely on three frameworks
* markdown for formatted text
* knitr for embedded R code
* YAML for render parameters

This analysis uses linear mixed modelling with restricted maximum likelihood (REML)

Read text in from file

allData <- read.delim("../data/n2a_dko_mutant_nmdar.dat", header = TRUE)
# Implicit nesting (required for anovaBF)
allData %>% 
  na.omit() %>%
  mutate(mutation = as.factor(mutation)) %>% 
  mutate(animal = paste0(as.numeric(mutation),animal)) %>% 
  mutate(slice = paste0(animal,slice)) %>% 
  mutate(pair = paste0(slice,pair)) %>% 
  mutate(pair = factor(pair)) -> Data

Factor encoding

Data$mutation <- as.factor(Data$mutation)
Data$transfection <- as.factor(Data$transfection)
Data$animal <- as.factor(Data$animal)
Data$slice <- as.factor(Data$slice)
Data$pair <- as.factor(Data$pair)

Set mutation WT and transfection - as reference levels

Data$mutation <- factor(Data$mutation, levels=c("WT","K669N","L812M","WT_2B"))
Data$transfection <- factor(Data$transfection, levels=c("-","+"))

lmer settings

settings <- lmerControl(check.conv.singular = .makeCC(action = "ignore",  tol = 1e-4), boundary.tol=0)

# Fit the model with planned contrasts and perform hypothesis testing
  
# Setup planned, orthogonal contrasts
# ("WT","K669N","L812M","WT_2B" )
# According to exploratory factor and cluster analysis of published data:
# GOF1 is gain-of-function (Factor 1)
# Factor 1 (functional change, e.g. EC50[Glu])
WT_vs_GOF1     <- c(-2,1,1,0)/3
GOF1           <- c(0,-1,1,0)/2
WT2B_vs_others <- c(1,1,1,-3)/4
contr.orth <- cbind(WT_vs_GOF1, GOF1, WT2B_vs_others)
rownames(contr.orth) <- levels(Data$mutation)

# Check that contrasts are indeed orthogonal
contr.orth %>%
  cor() %>%
  knitr::kable(caption = sprintf("**All off-diagonal elements in correlation matrix of orthogonal contrasts should be zero: %s**",resp), digits = 2) %>% 
  kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover")) %>%
  print()
contr.orth %>%
  colSums() %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rename(.,'sum' = '.') %>%
  knitr::kable(caption = sprintf("**Sum of each orthogonal contrast should be zero: %s**",resp), digits = 2) %>% 
  kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover")) %>%
  print()

# Fit full model (with orthogonal contrasts) optimizing the Maximum Likelihood criterion
contrasts(Data$mutation) <- contr.orth 
attr(Data$mutation,"contrasts") %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "mutation") %>% 
  knitr::kable(caption = sprintf("**Matrix of contrasts on mutation: %s**",resp), digits = 2) %>%

# Without random effects
formula <- sprintf("log(%s) ~ mutation * transfection", resp)
lm_model <- lm(formula, data = Data, na.action = "na.fail") 
# With random effects
formula <- sprintf("log(%s) ~ mutation * transfection + (1|animal/slice/pair)", resp)
lmer_model <- lmer(formula, data = Data, REML = FALSE, control = settings, na.action = "na.fail") 
# Compare models using information theory
AIC(lm_model,lmer_model) %>% 
  mutate(weight = exp(-0.5*(AIC-min(AIC)))) %>%
  mutate(weight = weight/sum(weight)) %>%
  knitr::kable(caption = sprintf("**Akaike information criterion (AIC) and Akaike weights for the full model with and without the random effects: %s**",resp), digits = 2) %>% 
  kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover")) %>%
  print()
BIC(lm_model,lmer_model) %>% 
  mutate(weight = exp(-0.5*(BIC-min(BIC)))) %>%
  mutate(weight = weight/sum(weight)) %>%
  knitr::kable(caption = sprintf("**Bayesian information criterion (BIC) and Schwarz weights for the full model with and without the random effects: %s**",resp), digits = 2) %>% 
  kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover")) %>%
  print()
# Compare residual standard
data.frame(sigma = c(sigma(lm_model), sigma(lmer_model)), row.names=c("lm_model","lmer_model"))  %>%
  mutate(percent = 100*sigma/max(sigma)) %>%
  knitr::kable(caption = sprintf("**Residual standard deviation for the full model with and without the random effects: %s**",resp), digits = 2) %>% 
  kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover")) %>%
  print()
# Assign lmer_model as model
model <- lmer_model

# Evaluate various other feasible models (with the different fixed effects) using information theory
# Compare model adequacy using the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) 
# AIC represents the amount of information lost when we use a model to approximate reality.
# The lower the value of AIC, the less the amount of information lost in using that model.
model.eval1 <- dredge(model, rank = "AIC") %>% 
  arrange(desc(df))
model.eval1 %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  mutate_if(is.double, formatC, format='f',digits = 2) %>%
  mutate_all(str_replace_all, pattern = "\\+", replacement = "\\\\+")  %>%  
  knitr::kable(caption = sprintf("**Akaike information criterion (AIC) and Akaike weights for the various possible models: %s**",resp), digits = 2) %>% 
  kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover")) %>%
  print()

# The Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC) measures the degree of belief that a certain model
# is the true data-generating model. The lower the value of BIC, the greater the belief.
# The BIC puts a unit information prior prior on parameters, which can be thought of as a
# prior distribution that contains the same amount of information as a single, typical 
# observation. This prior is quite diffuse.
model.eval2 <- dredge(model, rank = "BIC") %>% 
  arrange(desc(df))
model.eval2 %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  mutate_if(is.double, formatC, format='f',digits = 2) %>%
  mutate_all(str_replace_all, pattern = "\\+", replacement = "\\\\+")  %>%  
  knitr::kable(caption = sprintf("**Bayesian information criterion (BIC) and Schwarz weights for the various possible models: %s**",resp), digits = 2) %>% 
  kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover")) %>%
  print()

# Update model to remove the control (WT_2B) from the data set and contrasts since it will 
# make the omnibus test statistic obsolete and isn't be part of our hypothesis test
Data %>% 
  filter(mutation!="WT_2B") -> droppedData
droppedData$mutation <- factor(droppedData$mutation, levels = levels(droppedData$mutation)[-4])
contr.orth <- contr.orth[,-3] # remove contrast for 3rd column (contrast with level WT_2B)
contr.orth <- contr.orth[-4,] # remove contrast for 4th row (level WT_2B)
contrasts(droppedData$mutation) <- contr.orth 
model <- update(model, data = droppedData)

# Calculate ANOVA table for the fitted model (Type III sum of squares) 
car::Anova(model, type = 3, test.statistic = "F") %>%       # Uses Kenward-Roger degrees of freedom
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rownames_to_column(var="Source") %>%
  filter(Source != "(Intercept)") -> aov

# Calculate Bayes Factors for ANOVA and append them to the ANOVA data frame
# Inclusion Bayes Factor based on matched models (prior odds uniform-equal)
Data %>% 
  mutate(logresp = log(!!sym(resp))) %>%
  as.data.frame() -> Data
set.seed(123456)
anovaBF(logresp ~ mutation * transfection + animal + slice + pair, 
                 whichRandom = c("animal","slice","pair"), 
                 whichModels = "withmain", 
                 iterations = 20000,
                 data = Data) %>%
  bayesfactor_inclusion(match_models = TRUE) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  na.omit() %>%    # removes the (nuisance) random factors
  mutate(BF = exp(log_BF)) %>%
  mutate_at("BF", formatC, format='g',digits = 3) %>% 
  dplyr::select(BF) %>% 
  unlist() -> aov$BF

# Calculate intraclass correlation coefficients (ICC) for the random effects
icc(model, by_group=TRUE, tolerance=0) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  mutate(N = ngrps(model)) %>%
  rbind(.,c("residual",1-sum(.$ICC),nobs(model))) %>%
  mutate(ICC = as.numeric(ICC)) %>%                               
  knitr::kable(caption = sprintf("**Intraclass correlation coefficients for random effects: %s**",resp), digits = 3) %>% 
  kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover")) %>%
  print()

# 95% confidence intervals for interaction contrasts

emm.interaction <- contrast(emm, method = "trt.vs.ctrl", interaction = TRUE, adjust = "none")

# Standardized effect sizes (*r*) for interaction contrasts
# Methods used the same as this server: https://easystats4u.shinyapps.io/statistic2effectsize/
emm.interaction %>% 
    as.data.frame() %>% 
    mutate(n = df+nrow(.)+1) %>% 
    mutate(r = t_to_r(t.ratio, df)$r) %>% 
    mutate(z = atanh(r),
           SE = 1/sqrt(n-3),
           CI = sprintf("[%.2f, %.2f]",
                        LL = tanh(z - 1.96*SE),
                        UL = tanh(z + 1.96*SE))) %>%
    dplyr::select(-c(ratio,SE,df,null,t.ratio,p.value,z)) %>%
    knitr::kable(col.names = c("mutation",
                               "transfection",
                               "*n*",
                               "*r*",
                               "95% *CI*"),
                 caption = sprintf("**Standardized effect sizes (*r*) for contrasts: %s**",resp), digits = 2) %>% 
    kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover")) %>%
    print()

if (posthoc == TRUE) {
  
# p-values and maximum Bayes Factors for interaction contrasts 
# Westall stepwise adjustment to control FWER on p-values (using multcomp package)
# Chapter 4.1.2 in Bretz, F., Hothorn, T. and Westfall, P. (2011) Multiple Comparisons Using R. Taylor and Frances Group, LLC.
emm.interaction %>%   
    as.glht() %>%
    summary(test = adjusted(type = "Westfall")) -> glht.out  
emm.interaction %>%   
  as.data.frame() %>%
  dplyr::select(-SE) %>%
  mutate(p.adj = glht.out$test$pvalues) %>%
  mutate(p.adj = sapply(p.adj,max,.Machine$double.eps)) %>%
  mutate(maxBF = 1/pCalibrate(p.adj,"exploratory")) %>%
  mutate_at("maxBF", formatC, format='g',digits = 3) %>%
  mutate(p.value = afex::round_ps_apa(p.value)) %>%
  mutate(p.adj = afex::round_ps_apa(p.adj)) %>%
  knitr::kable(caption = sprintf("**Hypothesis testing on interaction parameters (Dunnett's step-down p-value adjustment): %s**",resp), digits = 2) %>%
  kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover")) %>%
  print()

}
